org.biopax.validator.rules

Class SharedUnificationXrefRule

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.biopax.validator.api.AbstractRule<org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.UnificationXref>
      • org.biopax.validator.rules.SharedUnificationXrefRule
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Rule<org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.UnificationXref>

    @Component
public class SharedUnificationXrefRule
extends AbstractRule<org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.UnificationXref>
    Checks whether more than one objects have the same UnificationXref, which violates UnificationXref semantics, unless these objects are, in fact, equivalent (despite their URIs are different) Although this rule is easy to check, auto-fixing is not that straightforward! We could replace the UnificationXref xref with new RelationshipXref (with the same db/id) for a pair of parent objects, such as, when the problematic unification xref is removed/replaced: - have different/incompatible BioPAX type, - may fix (unsafe), but it may be ok, e.g., for CVs; - are equivalent, i.e., they were also equivalent before, - do nothing; other rules may merge them; - are not equivalent but used to be equivalent, - do fix for sure; - are not equivalent, were not equivalent, but have the same type - fix (unsafe); It becomes hard to tell how to fix if there are more than two parents and various types... This rule won't fix, for it's unsafe; a data provider should take the warnings generated by this rule quite seriously and fix their BioPAX exporter.
    Author:
    rodche
